5000|$|<b>Locked-in</b> <b>syndrome</b> (LIS) is a {{condition}} in which a patient is aware but cannot move or communicate verbally due to complete paralysis of nearly all voluntary muscles in the body except for vertical eye movements and blinking. The individual is conscious and sufficiently intact cognitively to be able to communicate with eye movements. The EEG is normal in locked-in syndrome.Total <b>locked-in</b> <b>syndrome,</b> or completely locked-in state (CLIS), is a version of <b>locked-in</b> <b>syndrome</b> wherein the eyes are paralyzed as well. Fred Plum and Jerome Posner coined the term for this disorder in 1966.|$|E
